    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-12-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-12-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="409"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d409">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">310.2/12–1952</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Telephone Conversation, by <persName>Paul W.
                            Jones</persName> of the Office of United Nations Political and Security
                        Affairs</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-12-19">December 19,
                            1952</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <item>Subject:</item>
                    <item>Chinese Representation</item>
                </list>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_WENNERMA1">Wenner</persName> telephoned me on December
                    19 to inform me of the British position if the Chinese representation issue
                    should arise in the Fiscal Commission, Population Commission, Statistical
                    Commission and Transport and Communication Commission, which, he said, were
                    meeting in January or February of next year. He stated that the <gloss
                        target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> took the position that these bodies were not
                    competent to consider the Chinese representation issue and would support a
                    ruling to that effect should the issue arise. I told Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_WENNERMA1">Wenner</persName> that the United States also took
                    the position that these Commissions were not competent to consider the question
                    and that our Representatives would be so instructed.</p>
                <p>At one point in the conversation, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_WENNERMA1"
                        >Wenner</persName> alluded to “minor deviations” from the moratorium
                    arrangement recently and said that he wanted to be sure that the US and <gloss
                        target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> positions for the <gloss target="#t_ECOSOC1"
                        >ECOSOC</gloss> Commissions were coordinated. When I asked Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_WENNERMA1">Wenner</persName> what the deviations were, he said
                    that he was not concerned with that question at this point. (<hi rend="italic"
                        >Comment:</hi> Presumably Mr. <persName corresp="#p_WENNERMA1"
                        >Wenner</persName> was referring to the method of handling the Chinese
                    representation issue at the <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> and <gloss
                        target="#t_UNESCO1">UNESCO</gloss> to which the Foreign Office has objected.
                    However, I did not press him on the point since he obviously did not want to
                    discuss the matter.)</p>
            </div>
        </body>
